Getting Started with R

1. Welcome

This tutorial takes you throught the steps to get R and RStudio up and running on your Windows PC or Mac.

The figure below provides a visual representation of the relationship between R and RStudio. R is the engine that drives our calculations while RStudio is the interactive environment we use to interact with R.

The remainder of this tutorial will lead you through the steps to install R and the RStudio IDE. These steps apply if you have either a Mac or Windows PC. If you have a Chromebook or Linux computer, please contact me for help getting setup with R.

2. Installing R and RStudio

To install R and RStudio on your own computer, go to the site https://posit.co/download/rstudio-desktop/ and follow the instructions in the video here. Installation instructions focus on procedures for a Mac (if you have a Windows computer, here is the URL of a recent YouTube video that demonstrates the installation of R and RStudio on a Windows computer: https://youtu.be/YrEe2TLr3MI). Install the most recent version of the software that is compatible with your computer which may be newer than what you see in the video. Please note that as of December 11, 2023, the latest version of R is 4.3.2 and the latest version of RStudio is 2023.09.1+494. If you have any questions at this stage, feel free to reach out to me.

3. Installing R Packages

Once you will need to install a couple R packages. R packages are collections of functions and data sets developed by R users that increase the power of R by improving existing base R functions, add new functions, or bundle multiple datasets into a convenient “package.”

The next video (click here to access) takes you through the steps to install the two R packages we will use most: mosaic and Lock5Data. Package installation is a one-time operation. Once a package is installed, you do not need to re-install it each time you use R. But you do need to “load” packages at the beginning of your session and the templates I will provide for homework assignments will include lines that do that.

4. Next Steps

Now that you have completed these installations, you are ready to go. If you have run into problems or have questions, please contact me by Teams or email.
